def merge_holidays(df):
  merged_df = pd.merge(df, stores, on="store_nbr", suffixes=(None, None), copy=False)
  merged_df = pd.merge(merged_df, national, how='left', on="date", suffixes=(None, None), copy=False)
  merged_df = pd.merge(merged_df, regional, how='left', left_on=["date", "state"], right_on=["date", "locale_name"], suffixes=(None, None), copy=False)
  merged_df.drop(columns=["state","locale_name"], inplace=True)
  merged_df = pd.merge(merged_df, local, how='left', left_on=["date", "city"], right_on=["date", "locale_name"], suffixes=(None, None), copy=False)
  merged_df.drop(columns=["city", "locale_name"], inplace=True)
  merged_df[["National", "Regional", "Local"]] = merged_df[["National", "Regional", "Local"]].fillna(np.bool(False))
  merged_df['holiday'] = np.where((merged_df['National'] ==  np.bool(True)) | (merged_df['Regional'] == np.bool(True)) | (merged_df['Local'] == np.bool(True)), np.float(1), np.bool(0))
  merged_df.drop(columns=["National", "Regional", "Local"], inplace=True)
  merged_df['year'] = df['date'].dt.year
  merged_df['month'] = df['date'].dt.month
  merged_df['weekday'] = df['date'].dt.weekday
  merged_df.drop(columns=["date"], inplace=True)
  return merged_df

def plot_training(history):
  left_image = 0
  right_image = 1

  rmse = history.history['root_mean_squared_error']
  val_rmse = history.history['val_root_mean_squared_error']

  loss = history.history['loss']
  val_loss = history.history['val_loss']

  _, ax = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(10,4))
  ax[left_image].plot(rmse)
  ax[left_image].plot(val_rmse)
  ax[left_image].set_title('Model RMSE')
  ax[left_image].set_ylabel('Train RMSE')
  ax[left_image].set_xlabel('Epoch')
  ax[left_image].legend(['Train', 'Test'], loc='upper left')


  # Plot training & validation loss values
  ax[right_image].plot(loss)
  ax[right_image].plot(val_loss)
  ax[right_image].set_title('Model loss')
  ax[right_image].set_ylabel('Train Loss')
  ax[right_image].set_xlabel('Epoch')
  ax[right_image].legend(['Train', 'Test'], loc='upper left')

  plt.show()

  embedding = pd.DataFrame()

  embedding['s_enc'] = [store_enc[x] for x in df['store_nbr']]
  embedding['y_enc'] = [year_enc[x] for x in df['year']]
  embedding['m_enc'] = [month_enc[x] for x in df['month']]

def create_basic_model():
  x = concatenate([i, s])
  x = Flatten()(x)
  x = Dense(1, activation='relu')(x)
  nn = Model([item_in, store_in], x)
  nn.compile(Adam(0.001), loss='mse', metrics=[RootMeanSquaredError()])
  nn.summary()
  return nn

  nn.summary()

A word about Embedding and Bias:
An embedding is a mapping of a discrete — categorical — variable to a vector of continuous numbers. In the context of neural networks, embeddings are low-dimensional, learned continuous vector representations of discrete variables. Neural network embeddings are useful because they can reduce the dimensionality of categorical variables and meaningfully represent categories in the transformed space. 
[From Neural Network Embeddings Explained article.](https://towardsdatascience.com/neural-network-embeddings-explained-4d028e6f0526)

### Assignment 2 Summary
In this Assignment we expirienced . we had two types of tasks:

- The first task was a classification task based on  time-series learning. in this task we classified types of activities according to the PAMAP2 dataset, according to phisicaly sensors. we used LSTM layers with lookback sliding windows to predict type of activity according to many timesstamp samples.  After vreating a base model we tried to improve the model with fine tuning (pre-trained model of that predicted heart-rate according to other sensors) but the model scores did not improve. finally we improved our model slightly by increasing the lookback window, and also by deepening the layers and kernals. 

-  The second task we predicted unit sales for many items at different "Favorita" stores.  in this task we used Embedding to predict which items are going to be sold according to the data set of previous sales. after analyzing items and stores only, and basic result, we added other features as day, month and year of purchase as well as if the day of the purchase was a holiday or not. finally we used the pretrained model as a feature extractor for a classical ML algorithm(Decesion Tree Regressor).

Both tasks demanded preproccessing of large amount of data,  and create complex models to predict proper results.  We faced challanges when working on new types of layers and architectures, but got some good results.
